# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cox-proportional-hazards
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] A typical medical example would include covariates such as treatment assignment, as well as patient characteristics such as age at start of study, gender, and the presence of other diseases at start of study, in order to reduce variability and/or control for confounding.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The *proportional hazards condition* states that covariates are multiplicatively related to the hazard.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] In the simplest case of stationary coefficients, for example, a treatment with a drug may, say, halve a subject's hazard at any given time t , while the baseline hazard may vary.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Note however, that this does not double the lifetime of the subject; the precise effect of the covariates on the lifetime depends on the type of $\lambda _{0}(t)$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The covariate is not restricted to binary predictors; in the case of a continuous covariate x , it is typically assumed that the hazard responds exponentially; each unit increase in x results in proportional scaling of the hazard.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Sir David Cox observed that if the proportional hazards assumption holds (or, is assumed to hold) then it is possible to estimate the effect parameter(s), denoted $\beta _{i}$ below, without any consideration of the full hazard function.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] This approach to survival data is called application of the ***Cox proportional hazards model***, sometimes abbreviated to ***Cox model*** or to *proportional hazards model*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] However, Cox also noted that biological interpretation of the proportional hazards assumption can be quite tricky.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Let *X**i* = (*X**i*1, … , *X**ip*) be the realized values of the *p* covariates for subject *i*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Note that between subjects, the baseline hazard $\lambda _{0}(t)$ is identical (has no dependency on *i*).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The only difference between subjects' hazards comes from the baseline scaling factor $\exp(X_{i}\cdot \beta )$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] To start, suppose we only have a single covariate, x , and therefore a single coefficient, $\beta _{1}$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] We can see that increasing a covariate by 1 scales the original hazard by the constant $\exp(\beta _{1})$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The right-hand-side is constant over time (no term has a t in it).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] This relationship, $x/y={\text{constant}}$ , is called a proportional relationship.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] More generally, consider two subjects, *i* and *j*, with covariates $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ respectively.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The right-hand-side isn't dependent on time, as the only time-dependent factor, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , was cancelled out.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Thus the ratio of hazards of two subjects is a constant, i.e. the hazards are proportional.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Often there is an intercept term (also called a constant term or bias term) used in regression models.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The Cox model lacks one because the baseline hazard, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , takes the place of it.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Thus, the baseline hazard incorporates *all* parts of the hazard that are not dependent on the subjects' covariates, which includes any intercept term (which is constant for all subjects, by definition).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] In other words, adding an intercept term would make the model unidentifiable.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The Cox partial likelihood, shown below, is obtained by using Breslow's estimate of the baseline hazard function, plugging it into the full likelihood and then observing that the result is a product of two factors.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The first factor is the partial likelihood shown below, in which the baseline hazard has "canceled out".
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] It is simply the probability for subjects to have experienced events in the *order* that they actually have occurred, given the set of times of occurrences and given the subjects' covariates.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The second factor is free of the regression coefficients and depends on the data only through the censoring pattern.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The effect of covariates estimated by any proportional hazards model can thus be reported as hazard ratios.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] To calculate the partial likelihood, the probability for the order of events, let us index the *M* samples for which events have already occurred by increasing time of occurrence, *Y*1 < *Y*2 < ... < *Y*M.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Covariates of all other subjects for which no event has occurred get indices *M*+1,.., *N*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The partial likelihood can be factorized into one factor for each event that has occurred.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Treating the subjects as statistically independent of each other, the partial likelihood for the order of events is $L(\beta )=\prod _{i=1}^{M}L_{i}(\beta )=\prod _{i:C_{i}=1}L_{i}(\beta ),$ where the subjects for which an event has occurred are indicated by *C**i* = 1 and all others by *C**i* = 0.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The corresponding log partial likelihood is $\ell (\beta )=\sum _{i:C_{i}=1}\left(X_{i}\cdot \beta -\log \sum _{j:Y_{j}\geq Y_{i}}\theta _{j}\right),$ where we have written $\sum _{j=i}^{N}$ using the indexing introduced above in a more general way, as $\sum _{j:Y_{j}\geq Y_{i}}$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Crucially, the effect of the covariates can be estimated without the need to specify the hazard function $\lambda _{0}(t)$ over time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The partial likelihood can be maximized over *β* to produce maximum partial likelihood estimates of the model parameters.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Using this score function and Hessian matrix, the partial likelihood can be maximized using the Newton-Raphson algorithm.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The inverse of the Hessian matrix, evaluated at the estimate of *β*, can be used as an approximate variance-covariance matrix for the estimate, and used to produce approximate standard errors for the regression coefficients.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Several approaches have been proposed to handle situations in which there are ties in the time data.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] *Breslow's method* describes the approach in which the procedure described above is used unmodified, even when ties are present.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] An alternative approach that is considered to give better results is *Efron's method*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Let *t**j* denote the unique times, let *H**j* denote the set of indices *i* such that *Y**i* = *t**j* and *C**i* = 1, and let *m**j* = |*H**j*|.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Note that when *H**j* is empty (all observations with time *t**j* are censored), the summands in these expressions are treated as zero.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Below are some worked examples of the Cox model in practice.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Suppose the endpoint we are interested in is patient survival during a 5-year observation period after a surgery.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Patients can die within the 5-year period, and we record when they died, or patients can live past 5 years, and we only record that they lived past 5 years.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The surgery was performed at one of two hospitals, *A* or *B*, and we would like to know if the hospital location is associated with 5-year survival.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Specifically, we would like to know the *relative* increase (or decrease) in hazard from a surgery performed at hospital A compared to hospital B.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Provided is some (fake) data, where each row represents a patient: *T* is how long the patient was observed for before death or 5 years (measured in months), and *C* denotes if the patient died in the 5-year period.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] We have encoded the hospital as a binary variable denoted *X*: 1 if from hospital *A*, 0 from hospital *B*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Using statistical software, we can estimate $\beta _{1}$ to be 2.12.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The hazard ratio is the *exponential* of this value, $\exp(\beta _{1})=\exp(2.12)$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Thus, the hazard ratio of hospital A to hospital B is $\exp(2.12)=8.32$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Putting aside statistical significance for a moment, we can make a statement saying that patients in hospital A are associated with a 8.3x higher risk of death occurring in any short period of time compared to hospital B.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] More specifically, "risk of death" is a measure of a rate.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] A rate has units, like meters per second.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] However, a *relative* rate does not: a bicycle can go two times faster than another bicycle (the reference bicycle), without specifying any units.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Likewise, the risk of death (comparable to the speed of a bike) in hospital *A* is 8.3 times higher (faster) than the risk of death in hospital *B* (the reference group).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] We haven't made any inferences about *probabilities* of survival between the hospitals.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] This is because we would need an estimate of the baseline hazard rate, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , as well as our $\beta _{1}$ estimate.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] However, standard estimation of the Cox proportional hazard model does not directly estimate the baseline hazard rate.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Because we have ignored the only time varying component of the model, the baseline hazard rate, our estimate is timescale-invariant.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] For example, if we had measured time in years instead of months, we would get the same estimate.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] It is tempting to say that the hospital *caused* the difference in hazards between the two groups, but since our study is not causal (that is, we do not know how the data was generated), we stick with terminology like "associated".
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] To demonstrate a less traditional use case of survival analysis, the next example will be an economics question: what is the relationship between a company's price-to-earnings ratio (P/E) on their first IPO anniversary and their future survival?
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] More specifically, if we consider a company's "birth event" to be their first IPO anniversary, and any bankruptcy, sale, going private, etc. as a "death" event the company, we'd like to know the influence of the companies' P/E ratio at their "birth" (first IPO anniversary) on their survival.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Provided is a (fake) dataset with survival data from 12 companies: *T* represents the number of days between first IPO anniversary and death (or an end date of 2022-01-01, if did not die).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] *C* represents if the company died before 2022-01-01 or not.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] P/E represents the company's price-to-earnings ratio at its 1st IPO anniversary.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Unlike the previous example where there was a binary variable, this dataset has a continuous variable, P/E; however, the model looks similar: $\lambda (t|P_{i})=\lambda _{0}(t)\cdot \exp(\beta _{1}P_{i})$ where $P_{i}$ represents a company's P/E ratio.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Running this dataset through a Cox model produces an *estimate* of the value of the unknown $\beta _{1}$ , which is -0.34.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Since the baseline hazard, $\lambda _{0}(t)$ , was not estimated, the entire hazard is not able to be calculated.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] All terms on the right are known, so calculating the ratio of hazards between companies is possible.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Since there is no time-dependent term on the right (all terms are constant), the hazards are *proportional* to each other.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] This means that, within the interval of study, company 5's risk of "death" is 0.33 ≈ 1/3 as large as company 2's risk of death.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The baseline hazard can be represented when the scaling factor is 1, i.e. $P=0$ . $\lambda (t|P_{i}=0)=\lambda _{0}(t)\cdot \exp(-0.34\cdot 0)=\lambda _{0}(t)$ Can we interpret the baseline hazard as the hazard of a "baseline" company whose P/E happens to be 0?
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] This interpretation of the baseline hazard as "hazard of a baseline subject" is imperfect, as the covariate being 0 is impossible in this application: a P/E of 0 is meaningless (it means the company's stock price is 0, i.e., they are "dead").
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] A more appropriate interpretation would be "the hazard when all variables are nil".
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] It is tempting to want to understand and interpret a value like $\exp(\beta _{1}P_{i})$ to represent the hazard of a company.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] There is implicitly a ratio of hazards here, comparing company *i'*s hazard to an imaginary baseline company with 0 P/E.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] However, as explained above, a P/E of 0 is impossible in this application, so $\exp(\beta _{1}P_{i})$ is meaningless in this example.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Ratios between plausible hazards are meaningful, however.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Extensions to time dependent variables, time dependent strata, and multiple events per subject, can be incorporated by the counting process formulation of Andersen and Gill.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] One example of the use of hazard models with time-varying regressors is estimating the effect of unemployment insurance on unemployment spells.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] In addition to allowing time-varying covariates (i.e., predictors), the Cox model may be generalized to time-varying coefficients as well.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] That is, the proportional effect of a treatment may vary with time; e.g. a drug may be very effective if administered within one month of morbidity, and become less effective as time goes on.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The hypothesis of no change with time (stationarity) of the coefficient may then be tested.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Details and software (R package) are available in Martinussen and Scheike (2006).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Perhaps as a result of this complication, such models are seldom seen.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] If the objective is instead least squares the non-negativity restriction is not strictly required.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The Cox model may be specialized if a reason exists to assume that the baseline hazard follows a particular form.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] In this case, the baseline hazard $\lambda _{0}(t)$ is replaced by a given function.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] For example, assuming the hazard function to be the *Weibull* hazard function gives the *Weibull proportional hazards model*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Incidentally, using the Weibull baseline hazard is the only circumstance under which the model satisfies both the proportional hazards, and accelerated failure time models.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The generic term *parametric proportional hazards models* can be used to describe proportional hazards models in which the hazard function is specified.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The Cox proportional hazards model is sometimes called a *semiparametric model* by contrast.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Some authors use the term *Cox proportional hazards model* even when specifying the underlying hazard function, to acknowledge the debt of the entire field to David Cox.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The term *Cox regression model* (omitting *proportional hazards*) is sometimes used to describe the extension of the Cox model to include time-dependent factors.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] However, this usage is potentially ambiguous since the Cox proportional hazards model can itself be described as a regression model.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] There is a relationship between proportional hazards models and Poisson regression models which is sometimes used to fit approximate proportional hazards models in software for Poisson regression.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] The usual reason for doing this is that calculation is much quicker.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] This was more important in the days of slower computers but can still be useful for particularly large data sets or complex problems.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Laird and Olivier (1981) provide the mathematical details.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] They note, "we do not assume [the Poisson model] is true, but simply use it as a device for deriving the likelihood." McCullagh and Nelder's book on generalized linear models has a chapter on converting proportional hazards models to generalized linear models.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] In high-dimension, when number of covariates p is large compared to the sample size n, the LASSO method is one of the classical model-selection strategies.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] Tibshirani (1997) has proposed a Lasso procedure for the proportional hazard regression parameter.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/cox-regression] There has been theoretical progress on this topic recently.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] In survival analysis, the **hazard ratio** (**HR**) is the ratio of the hazard rates corresponding to the conditions characterised by two distinct levels of a treatment variable of interest.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For example, in a clinical study of a drug, the treated population may die at twice the rate of the control population.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The hazard ratio would be 2, indicating a higher hazard of death from the treatment.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] So, for a hazardous outcome (e.g., severe disease or death), an HR below 1 indicates that the treatment (e.g., vaccination) is protective against the outcome of interest.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] In other cases, an HR greater than 1 indicates the treatment is favorable.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For example, if the outcome is actually favorable (e.g., accepting a job offer to end a spell of unemployment), an HR greater than 1 indicates that seeking a job is favorable to not seeking one (if "treatment" is defined as seeking a job).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios differ from relative risks (RRs) and odds ratios (ORs) in that RRs and ORs are cumulative over an entire study, using a defined endpoint, while HRs represent instantaneous risk over the study time period, or some subset thereof.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios suffer somewhat less from selection bias with respect to the endpoints chosen and can indicate risks that happen before the endpoint.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Regression models are used to obtain hazard ratios and their confidence intervals.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] where *N*(*t*) is the number at risk at the beginning of an interval.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] A hazard is the probability that a patient fails between t and $t+\Delta t$ , given that they have survived up to time t , divided by $\Delta t$ , as $\Delta t$ approaches zero.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Such models are generally classed proportional hazards regression models; the best known being the Cox proportional hazards model, and the exponential, Gompertz and Weibull parametric models.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For two groups that differ only in treatment condition, the ratio of the hazard functions is given by $e^{\beta }$ , where $\beta$ is the estimate of treatment effect derived from the regression model.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] This hazard ratio, that is, the ratio between the predicted hazard for a member of one group and that for a member of the other group, is given by holding everything else constant, i.e. assuming proportionality of the hazard functions.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For a continuous explanatory variable, the same interpretation applies to a unit difference.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Other HR models have different formulations and the interpretation of the parameter estimates differs accordingly.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] In its simplest form, the hazard ratio can be interpreted as the chance of an event occurring in the treatment arm divided by the chance of the event occurring in the control arm, or vice versa, of a study.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The resolution of these endpoints are usually depicted using Kaplan–Meier survival curves.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] These curves relate the proportion of each group where the endpoint has not been reached.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The endpoint could be any dependent variable associated with the covariate (independent variable), e.g. death, remission of disease or contraction of disease.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The curve represents the odds of an endpoint having occurred at each point in time (the hazard).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The hazard ratio is simply the relationship between the instantaneous hazards in the two groups and represents, in a single number, the magnitude of distance between the Kaplan–Meier plots.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios do not reflect a time unit of the study.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The difference between hazard-based and time-based measures is akin to the difference between the odds of winning a race and the margin of victory.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] When a study reports one hazard ratio per time period, it is assumed that difference between groups was proportional.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios become meaningless when this assumption of proportionality is not met.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] If the proportional hazard assumption holds, a hazard ratio of one means equivalence in the hazard rate of the two groups, whereas a hazard ratio other than one indicates difference in hazard rates between groups.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The researcher indicates the probability of this sample difference being due to chance by reporting the probability associated with some test statistic.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For instance, the $\beta$ from the Cox-model or the log-rank test might then be used to assess the significance of any differences observed in these survival curves.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Conventionally, probabilities lower than 0.05 are considered significant and researchers provide a 95% confidence interval for the hazard ratio, e.g. derived from the standard deviation of the Cox-model regression coefficient, i.e. $\beta$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Statistically significant hazard ratios cannot include unity (one) in their confidence intervals.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The proportional hazards assumption for hazard ratio estimation is strong and often unreasonable.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Complications, adverse effects and late effects are all possible causes of change in the hazard rate over time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For instance, a surgical procedure may have high early risk, but excellent long term outcomes.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] If the hazard ratio between groups remain constant, this is not a problem for interpretation.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] However, interpretation of hazard ratios become impossible when selection bias exists between groups.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For instance, a particularly risky surgery might result in the survival of a systematically more robust group who would have fared better under any of the competing treatment conditions, making it look as if the risky procedure was better.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] A cancer treatment associated with better remission rates might on follow-up be associated with higher relapse rates.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The researchers' decision about when to follow up is arbitrary and may lead to very different reported hazard ratios.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Hazard ratios are often treated as a ratio of death probabilities.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] For example, a hazard ratio of 2 may mistakenly be thought to mean that a group has twice the chance of dying than a comparison group.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] To see why this is wrong, we consider a case when the proportional hazard assumption holds.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] In that case the hazard ratio can be shown to translate to the following relationship between group survival functions: $S_{1}(t)=S_{0}(t)^{r}$ (where *r* is the hazard ratio).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The corresponding death probabilities are 0.8 and 0.96.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] It should be clear that the hazard ratio is a relative measure of effect and is not a measure of absolute risk.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] While hazard ratios allow for hypothesis testing, they should be considered alongside other measures for interpretation of the treatment effect, e.g. the ratio of median times (median ratio) at which treatment and control group participants are at some endpoint.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] If the analogy of a race is applied, the hazard ratio is equivalent to the odds that an individual in the group with the higher hazard reaches the end of the race first.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] In the previous example, a hazard ratio of 2 corresponds to a 67% chance of an early death.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The hazard ratio does not convey information about how soon the death will occur.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Treatment effect depends on the underlying disease related to survival function, not just the hazard ratio.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] Since the hazard ratio does not give us direct time-to-event information, researchers have to report median endpoint times and calculate the median endpoint time ratio by dividing the control group median value by the treatment group median value.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] While the median endpoint ratio is a relative speed measure, the hazard ratio is not.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] The relationship between treatment effect and the hazard ratio is given as $e^{\beta }$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] A statistically important, but practically insignificant effect can produce a large hazard ratio, e.g. a treatment increasing the number of one-year survivors in a population from one in 10,000 to one in 1,000 has a hazard ratio of 10.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] It is unlikely that such a treatment would have had much impact on the median endpoint time ratio, which likely would have been close to unity, i.e. mortality was largely the same regardless of group membership and clinically insignificant.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] By contrast, a treatment group in which 50% of infections are resolved after one week (versus 25% in the control) yields a hazard ratio of two.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/hazard-ratio] If it takes ten weeks for all cases in the treatment group and half of cases in the control group to resolve, the ten-week hazard ratio remains at two, but the median endpoint time ratio is ten, a clinically significant difference.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Concretely, partial likelihood estimation uses the product of conditional densities as the density of the joint conditional distribution.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] This generality facilitates maximum likelihood methods in panel data setting because fully specifying conditional distribution of *yi* can be computationally demanding.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] On the other hand, allowing for misspecification generally results in violation of information equality and thus requires use of robust standard error estimators for inference.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] In the following exposition, we follow the treatment in Wooldridge.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Particularly, the asymptotic derivation is done under fixed-T, growing-N setting.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] In this formulation, the joint conditional density of *yi* given *xi* is modeled as *Πt* *ft* (*yit* | *xit* ; θ).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] We assume that *ft (yit |xit ; θ)* is correctly specified for each *t* = 1,...,*T* and that there exists *θ0* ∈ Θ that uniquely maximizes *E[ft (yit│xit ; θ)]*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] But, it is not assumed that the joint conditional density is correctly specified.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Under some regularity conditions, partial MLE is consistent and asymptotically normal.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] By the usual argument for M-estimators (details in Wooldridge ), the asymptotic variance of √*N* *(θMLE- θ0) is A−1 BA−1* where *A−1 = E[ Σt∇2θ logft (yit│xit ; θ)]−1 and B=E[( Σt∇θ logft (yit│xit ; θ) ) ( Σt∇θ logft (yit│xit; θ ) )T]*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] If the joint conditional density of yi given xi is correctly specified, the above formula for asymptotic variance simplifies because information equality says *B=A*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Yet, except for special circumstances, the joint density modeled by partial MLE is not correct.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Therefore, for valid inference, the above formula for asymptotic variance should be used.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] For information equality to hold, one sufficient condition is that scores of the densities for each time period are uncorrelated.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] In dynamically complete models, the condition holds and thus simplified asymptotic variance is valid.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Pooled QMLE is a technique that allows estimating parameters when panel data is available with Poisson outcomes.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] For instance, one might have information on the number of patents files by a number of different firms over time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Pooled QMLE does not necessarily contain unobserved effects (which can be either random effects or fixed effects), and the estimation method is mainly proposed for these purposes.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] The computational requirements are less stringent, especially compared to fixed-effect Poisson models, but the trade off is the possibly strong assumption of no unobserved heterogeneity.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Pooled refers to pooling the data over the different time periods *T*, while QMLE refers to the quasi-maximum likelihood technique.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] the starting point for Poisson pooled QMLE is the conditional mean assumption.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] The compact parameter space condition is imposed to enable the use of M-estimation techniques, while the conditional mean reflects the fact that the population mean of a Poisson process is the parameter of interest.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] In this particular case, the parameter governing the Poisson process is allowed to vary with respect to the vector $x_{t}\centerdot$ .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] The function *m* can, in principle, change over time even though it is often specified as static over time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] Note that only the conditional mean function is specified, and we will get consistent estimates of $b_{0}$ as long as this mean condition is correctly specified.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] A popular choice is $m=(x_{t},b_{0})=\exp(x_{t}b_{0})$ , as Poisson processes are defined over the positive real line.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/partial-likelihood] This reduces the conditional moment to an exponential index function, where $x_{t}b_{0}$ is the linear index and exp is the link function.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] To answer such questions, it is necessary to define "lifetime".
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the case of biological survival, death is unambiguous, but for mechanical reliability, failure may not be well-defined, for there may well be mechanical systems in which failure is partial, a matter of degree, or not otherwise localized in time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Even in biological problems, some events (for example, heart attack or other organ failure) may have the same ambiguity.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The theory outlined below assumes well-defined events at specific times; other cases may be better treated by models which explicitly account for ambiguous events.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] More generally, survival analysis involves the modelling of time to event data; in this context, death or failure is considered an "event" in the survival analysis literature – traditionally only a single event occurs for each subject, after which the organism or mechanism is dead or broken.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] *Recurring event* or *repeated event* models relax that assumption.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The study of recurring events is relevant in systems reliability, and in many areas of social sciences and medical research.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This example uses the Acute Myelogenous Leukemia survival data set "aml" from the "survival" package in R.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The data set is from Miller (1997) and the question is whether the standard course of chemotherapy should be extended ('maintained') for additional cycles.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The aml data set sorted by survival time is shown in the box.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The last observation (11), at 161 weeks, is censored.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Censoring indicates that the patient did not have an event (no recurrence of aml cancer).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Another subject, observation 3, was censored at 13 weeks (indicated by status=0).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This subject was in the study for only 13 weeks, and the aml cancer did not recur during those 13 weeks.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] It is possible that this patient was enrolled near the end of the study, so that they could be observed for only 13 weeks.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] It is also possible that the patient was enrolled early in the study, but was lost to follow up or withdrew from the study.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The table shows that other subjects were censored at 16, 28, and 45 weeks (observations 17, 6, and 9 with status=0).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The remaining subjects all experienced events (recurrence of aml cancer) while in the study.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The question of interest is whether recurrence occurs later in maintained patients than in non-maintained patients.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The survival function *S*(*t*), is the probability that a subject survives longer than time *t*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] *S*(*t*) is theoretically a smooth curve, but it is usually estimated using the Kaplan–Meier (KM) curve.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] A life table summarizes survival data in terms of the number of events and the proportion surviving at each event time point.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The life table for the aml data, created using the R software, is shown.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The life table summarizes the events and the proportion surviving at each event time point.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The log-rank test compares the survival times of two or more groups.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This example uses a log-rank test for a difference in survival in the maintained versus non-maintained treatment groups in the aml data.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The graph shows KM plots for the aml data broken out by treatment group, which is indicated by the variable "x" in the data.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The null hypothesis for a log-rank test is that the groups have the same survival.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The expected number of subjects surviving at each time point in each is adjusted for the number of subjects at risk in the groups at each event time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The log-rank test determines if the observed number of events in each group is significantly different from the expected number.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The formal test is based on a chi-squared statistic.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] When the log-rank statistic is large, it is evidence for a difference in the survival times between the groups.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The log-rank statistic approximately has a Chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom, and the p-value is calculated using the Chi-squared test.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For the example data, the log-rank test for difference in survival gives a p-value of p=0.0653, indicating that the treatment groups do not differ significantly in survival, assuming an alpha level of 0.05.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The sample size of 23 subjects is modest, so there is little power to detect differences between the treatment groups.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The chi-squared test is based on asymptotic approximation, so the p-value should be regarded with caution for small sample sizes.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Kaplan–Meier curves and log-rank tests are most useful when the predictor variable is categorical (e.g., drug vs. placebo), or takes a small number of values (e.g., drug doses 0, 20, 50, and 100 mg/day) that can be treated as categorical.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The log-rank test and KM curves don't work easily with quantitative predictors such as gene expression, white blood count, or age.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For quantitative predictor variables, an alternative method is Cox proportional hazards regression analysis.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Cox PH models work also with categorical predictor variables, which are encoded as {0,1} indicator or dummy variables.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The log-rank test is a special case of a Cox PH analysis, and can be performed using Cox PH software.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This example uses the melanoma data set from Dalgaard Chapter 14.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Cox proportional hazards regression using R gives the results shown in the box.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Cox regression results are interpreted as follows.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The summary output also gives upper and lower 95% confidence intervals for the hazard ratio: lower 95% bound = 1.15; upper 95% bound = 3.26.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] These three tests are asymptotically equivalent.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For large enough N, they will give similar results.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The last row, "Score (logrank) test" is the result for the log-rank test, with p=0.011, the same result as the log-rank test, because the log-rank test is a special case of a Cox PH regression.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Likelihood ratio test has better behavior for small sample sizes, so it is generally preferred.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Cox model extends the log-rank test by allowing the inclusion of additional covariates.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This example uses the melanoma data set where the predictor variables include a continuous covariate, the thickness of the tumor (variable name = "thick").
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the histograms, the thickness values are positively skewed and do not have a Gaussian-like, symmetric probability distribution.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Regression models, including the Cox model, generally give more reliable results with normally-distributed variables.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For this example we may use a logarithmic transform.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The log of the thickness of the tumor looks to be more normally distributed, so the Cox models will use log thickness.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Cox PH analysis using R gives the results below.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The p-value for all three overall tests (likelihood, Wald, and score) are significant, indicating that the model is significant.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The p-value for $\log({\text{thick}})$ is 6.94×10−7, with a hazard ratio $HR=\exp({\text{coef}})=2.183$ , indicating a strong relationship between the thickness of the tumor and increased risk of death.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Because the confidence interval for HR includes 1, these results indicate that sex makes a smaller contribution to the difference in the HR after controlling for the thickness of the tumor.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Examination of graphs of $log({\text{thick}})$ by sex and a t-test of $log({\text{thick}})$ by sex both indicate that there is a significant difference between men and women in the thickness of the tumor when they first see the clinician.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Cox model assumes that the hazards are proportional.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The proportional hazard assumption may be tested using the R function `cox.zph()` from the survival R package.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] A p-value which is less than 0.05 indicates that the hazards are not proportional.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For the melanoma data, we obtain $p=0.248$ for sex.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Hence, we cannot reject the null hypothesis of the hazards of sex being proportional.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Cox models can be extended to deal with variations on the simple analysis.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Cox PH regression model is a linear model.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] It is similar to linear regression and logistic regression.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Specifically, these methods assume that a single line, curve, plane, or surface is sufficient to separate groups (alive, dead) or to estimate a quantitative response (survival time).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In some cases alternative partitions give more accurate classification or quantitative estimates.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] One set of alternative methods are tree-structured survival models, including survival random forests.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Tree-structured survival models may give more accurate predictions than Cox models.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Examining both types of models for a given data set is a reasonable strategy.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This example of a survival tree analysis uses the R package "rpart".
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The example is based on 146 stage C prostate cancer patients in the data set stagec in rpart.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Rpart and the stagec example are described in Atkinson and Therneau (1997), which is also distributed as a vignette of the rpart package.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The survival tree produced by the analysis is shown in the figure.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Each branch in the tree indicates a split on the value of a variable.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For example, the root of the tree splits subjects with grade < 2.5 versus subjects with grade 2.5 or greater.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The terminal nodes indicate the number of subjects in the node, the number of subjects who have events, and the relative event rate compared to the root.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the node on the far left, the values 1/33 indicate that one of the 33 subjects in the node had an event, and that the relative event rate is 0.122.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the node on the far right bottom, the values 11/15 indicate that 11 of 15 subjects in the node had an event, and the relative event rate is 2.7.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] An alternative to building a single survival tree is to build many survival trees, where each tree is constructed using a sample of the data, and average the trees to predict survival.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This is the method underlying the survival random forest models.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Survival random forest analysis is available in the R package "randomForestSRC".
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The randomForestSRC package includes an example survival random forest analysis using the data set pbc.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This data is from the Mayo Clinic Primary Biliary Cirrhosis (PBC) trial of the liver conducted between 1974 and 1984.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the example, the random forest survival model gives more accurate predictions of survival than the Cox PH model.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The prediction errors are estimated by bootstrap re-sampling.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Recent advancements in deep representation learning have been extended to survival estimation.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The DeepSurv model proposes to replace the log-linear parameterization of the CoxPH model with a multi-layer perceptron.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Further extensions like Deep Survival Machines and Deep Cox Mixtures involve the use of latent variable mixture models to model the time-to-event distribution as a mixture of parametric or semi-parametric distributions while jointly learning representations of the input covariates.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Deep learning approaches have shown superior performance especially on complex input data modalities such as images and clinical time-series.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The object of primary interest is the **survival function**, conventionally denoted *S*, which is defined as $S(t)=\Pr(T>t)$ where *t* is some time, *T* is a random variable denoting the time of death, or more generally any event, and "Pr" stands for probability.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] That is, the survival function is the probability of observing an event time greater than some specified time *t*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The survival function is also called the *survivor function* or *survivorship function* in problems of biological survival, and the *reliability function* in mechanical survival problems.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the latter case, the reliability function is denoted *R*(*t*).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Usually one assumes *S*(0) = 1, although it could be less than 1 if there is the possibility of immediate death or failure.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The survival function must be non-increasing: *S*(*u*) ≤ *S*(*t*) if *u* ≥ *t*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This property follows directly because *T*>*u* implies *T*>*t*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This reflects the notion that survival to a later age is possible only if all younger ages are attained.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Given this property, the lifetime distribution function and event density (*F* and *f* below) are well-defined.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The survival function is usually assumed to approach zero as age increases without bound (i.e., *S*(*t*) → 0 as *t* → ∞), although the limit could be greater than zero if eternal life is possible.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For instance, we could apply survival analysis to a mixture of stable and unstable carbon isotopes; unstable isotopes would decay sooner or later, but the stable isotopes would last indefinitely.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Related quantities are defined in terms of the survival function.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] $f(t)=F'(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}F(t).$ The function *f* is sometimes called the **event density**; it is the rate of death or failure events per unit time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] $s(t)=S'(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}S(t)={\frac {d}{dt}}\int _{t}^{\infty }f(u)\,du={\frac {d}{dt}}[1-F(t)]=-f(t).$ In other fields, such as statistical physics, the survival event density function is known as the first passage time density.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Synonyms for *hazard function* in different fields include hazard rate, intensity function, force of mortality (demography and actuarial science, denoted by $\mu$ ), force of failure, or failure rate (engineering, denoted $\lambda$ ).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For example, in actuarial science, $\mu (x)$ denotes rate of death for people aged x , whereas in reliability engineering $\lambda (t)$ denotes rate of failure of components after operation for time t .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The hazard function represents the probability that a subject will experience an event in the next small interval of time, divided by the length of this interval, given that they have survived up to time t .
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] where Bayes' theorem, and identifying $\Pr(T>t)$ as the survival function, has been used in the first equality, and the definition of the density function of the lifetime distribution in the second.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In fact, the hazard rate is usually more informative about the underlying mechanism of failure than the other representations of a lifetime distribution.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The hazard function must be non-negative, $\lambda (t)\geq 0$ , and its integral over $[0,\infty ]$ must be infinite, but is not otherwise constrained; it may be increasing or decreasing, non-monotonic, or discontinuous.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] An example is the bathtub curve hazard function, which is large for small values of t , decreasing to some minimum, and thereafter increasing again; this can model the property of some mechanical systems to either fail soon after operation, or much later, as the system ages.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] $\Lambda (t)=\int _{0}^{t}\lambda (u)\,du$ which is the "accumulation" of the hazard over time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] From the definition of $\Lambda (t)$ , we see that it increases without bound as *t* tends to infinity (assuming that $S(t)$ tends to zero).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This implies that $\lambda (t)$ must not decrease too quickly, since, by definition, the cumulative hazard has to diverge.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For example, $\exp(-t)$ is not the hazard function of any survival distribution, because its integral converges to 1.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For $t_{0}=0$ , that is, at birth, this reduces to the expected lifetime.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In reliability problems, the expected lifetime is called the *mean time to failure*, and the expected future lifetime is called the *mean residual lifetime*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] As the probability of an individual surviving until age *t* or later is *S*(*t*), by definition, the expected number of survivors at age *t* out of an initial population of *n* newborns is *n* × *S*(*t*), assuming the same survival function for all individuals.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Thus the expected proportion of survivors is *S*(*t*).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] If the survival of different individuals is independent, the number of survivors at age *t* has a binomial distribution with parameters *n* and *S*(*t*), and the variance of the proportion of survivors is *S*(*t*) × (1-*S*(*t*))/*n*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The age at which a specified proportion of survivors remain can be found by solving the equation *S*(*t*) = *q* for *t*, where *q* is the quantile in question.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Typically one is interested in the **median lifetime**, for which *q* = 1/2, or other quantiles such as *q* = 0.90 or *q* = 0.99.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Censoring is a form of missing data problem in which time to event is not observed for reasons such as termination of study before all recruited subjects have shown the event of interest or the subject has left the study prior to experiencing an event.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Censoring is common in survival analysis.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] If only the lower limit *l* for the true event time *T* is known such that *T* > *l*, this is called *right censoring*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Right censoring will occur, for example, for those subjects whose birth date is known but who are still alive when they are lost to follow-up or when the study ends.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] We generally encounter right-censored data.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] If the event of interest has already happened before the subject is included in the study but it is not known when it occurred, the data is said to be *left-censored*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] When it can only be said that the event happened between two observations or examinations, this is *interval censoring*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Left censoring occurs for example when a permanent tooth has already emerged prior to the start of a dental study that aims to estimate its emergence distribution.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In the same study, an emergence time is interval-censored when the permanent tooth is present in the mouth at the current examination but not yet at the previous examination.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Interval censoring often occurs in HIV/AIDS studies.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Indeed, time to HIV seroconversion can be determined only by a laboratory assessment which is usually initiated after a visit to the physician.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Then one can only conclude that HIV seroconversion has happened between two examinations.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The same is true for the diagnosis of AIDS, which is based on clinical symptoms and needs to be confirmed by a medical examination.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] It may also happen that subjects with a lifetime less than some threshold may not be observed at all: this is called *truncation*.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Note that truncation is different from left censoring, since for a left censored datum, we know the subject exists, but for a truncated datum, we may be completely unaware of the subject.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In a so-called *delayed entry* study, subjects are not observed at all until they have reached a certain age.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For example, people may not be observed until they have reached the age to enter school.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Any deceased subjects in the pre-school age group would be unknown.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Left-truncated data are common in actuarial work for life insurance and pensions.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Left-censored data can occur when a person's survival time becomes incomplete on the left side of the follow-up period for the person.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] For example, in an epidemiological example, we may monitor a patient for an infectious disorder starting from the time when he or she is tested positive for the infection.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Although we may know the right-hand side of the duration of interest, we may never know the exact time of exposure to the infectious agent.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Survival models can be usefully viewed as ordinary regression models in which the response variable is time.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] However, computing the likelihood function (needed for fitting parameters or making other kinds of inferences) is complicated by the censoring.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The likelihood function for a survival model, in the presence of censored data, is formulated as follows.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] By definition the likelihood function is the conditional probability of the data given the parameters of the model.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] It is customary to assume that the data are independent given the parameters.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Then the likelihood function is the product of the likelihood of each datum.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] It is convenient to partition the data into four categories: uncensored, left censored, right censored, and interval censored.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] These are denoted "unc.", "l.c.", "r.c.", and "i.c." in the equation below.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Kaplan–Meier estimator can be used to estimate the survival function.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The Nelson–Aalen estimator can be used to provide a non-parametric estimate of the cumulative hazard rate function.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Periodic case (cohort) and death (and recovery) counts are statistically sufficient to make nonparametric maximum likelihood and least squares estimates of survival functions, without lifetime data.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] While many parametric models assume a continuous-time, discrete-time survival models can be mapped to a binary classification problem.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] In a discrete-time survival model the survival period is artificially resampled in intervals where for each interval a binary target indicator is recorded if the event takes place in a certain time horizon.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] If a binary classifier (potentially enhanced with a different likelihood to take more structure of the problem into account) is calibrated, then the classifier score is the hazard function (i.e. the conditional probability of failure).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Discrete-time survival models are connected to empirical likelihood.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Instead of performing the time-discretization and bringing the data in this long-format, an alternative way is to perform distributional regression over the binned time-axis.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This approach can leverage prior data fitted networks (tabular foundation models) to work with small data sets already.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The goodness of fit of survival models can be assessed using scoring rules.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] A cure model allows for the possibility that some individuals never experience the event of interest.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] This creates survival curves that plateau rather than always converging to zero.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] First term: cured individuals, who survive indefinitely.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Second term: susceptible individuals, whose survival declines according to the hazard.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] Without a cure model, survival is forced to zero in the limit of large times.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The textbook by Kleinbaum has examples of survival analyses using SAS, R, and other packages.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/survival-analysis] The textbooks by Brostrom, Dalgaard and Tableman and Kim give examples of survival analyses using R (or using S, and which run in R).
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] A **time-varying covariate** (also called **time-dependent covariate**) is a term used in statistics, particularly in survival analysis.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] It reflects the phenomenon that a covariate is not necessarily constant through the whole study Time-varying covariates are included to represent time-dependent within-individual variation to predict individual responses.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] For instance, if one wishes to examine the link between area of residence and cancer, this would be complicated by the fact that study subjects move from one area to another.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] The area of residency could then be introduced in the statistical model as a time-varying covariate.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] In survival analysis, this would be done by splitting each study subject into several observations, one for each area of residence.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] For example, if a person is born at time 0 in area A, moves to area B at time 5, and is diagnosed with cancer at time 8, two observations would be made.
[src:cox-proportional-hazards/time-varying-covariate] One with a length of 5 (5 − 0) in area A, and one with a length of 3 (8 − 5) in area B.
